    <div class="project-grid">

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Project Overview</h2>
        <p>Werken bij Schiphol was part of a broader career orientation platform called Beroeps Orientatie — a digital environment designed to help students explore different career paths and orient themselves in the job market. For the Schiphol component, the goal was to shine a light on the many behind-the-scenes roles at Amsterdam Airport Schiphol that most people never see. The result was a 360° interactive tour: users navigate through 360-degree still images of real airport locations, similar to Google Street View, with people placed inside each scene. Clicking on a person plays a video of that employee answering questions about what their job actually involves.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Client &amp; Context</h2>
        <p>The platform was initiated by Fleur, who envisioned a full suite of career experiences across different industries that schools could licence and use with their students. The Schiphol group was one of the first clients on the platform, motivated by a desire to recruit for roles that rarely get any public attention. The recordings took place on location at Schiphol Airport, with real employees from various departments agreeing to be filmed talking about their work.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Goals &amp; Challenges</h2>
        <p>The core challenge was capturing professional-quality greenscreen footage in a completely improvised setting — a standard conference room at the airport, far from any studio environment. Getting the lighting even enough to pull a clean key was difficult without dedicated equipment. On top of that, many of the employees being filmed were not used to being in front of a camera, so drawing out natural and engaging answers from them took patience and direction. The logistics were also demanding: living in Limburg and travelling to Schiphol for early-morning shoots made for 14-hour working days. An additional complication arose around equipment: the first camera used was too low in quality, so a phone was used for subsequent sessions to get 4K footage — a practical solution that nonetheless drew complaints from the client, who felt it did not look sufficiently professional.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Technical Details</h2>
        <p>The role on this project was on-site camera operator and video editor. A portable greenscreen kit was set up at Schiphol for each recording day, with lighting adjusted as best as possible within the available space. After filming, all footage was brought back and edited — greenscreen backgrounds were keyed out, audio recordings were cleaned and synced, and the final clips were formatted for integration into the 360° tour platform.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Reflection</h2>
        <p>This project highlighted how much the perceived professionalism of a production is tied to the quality of the equipment used — regardless of the actual result. Even when the phone footage was technically superior to the first camera, the client's perception was shaped by the tool rather than the output. The experience reinforced the value of always arriving on set with professional, recognisable gear, and the importance of managing client expectations around the practical realities of location shooting.</p>
      </section>

